column3: When introducing the U.S. women's movement, you recognize from the outset the drawbacks and criticism facing this "wave" lens of analysis. It appears that this framework effectively highlights a social movement form as shaped by the white middle-class women. Yet, in the U.S. there is a long track record of white activists re-engineering (or rebranding or reprioritizing) social movement forms in which working class people/people of color had already completed significant amounts of organizing and work - to make the movement more palatable to white mainstream America. For example, Gay Liberation was overhauled as a gay rights movement and priorities shifted from universal healthcare and anti-racism to same-sex marriage. Was it a concern for you that using this framework of analysis possibly over emphasizes the contributions of white feminist activists and organizations? How did you reconcile using the wave framework while still attempting to capture a representative essence of the movement?

column3: Hi team! I'm currently moving house, but I'm hoping to get a new version up by the end of the month. The move is going to give me a couple more free hours every day, and I would like to be more active on this again. That said, it's really not fair to anyone that updates are entirely dependent on my personal schedule. There's a few ways we can mitigate this without giving any one person total control of the project, and I thought it was worth discussing. One options is that we either find (or found) a small LGBT organisation to manage this aspect, and the members of that organisation would be responsible for pushing updates to the web stores. Another option is that we set up [Group Publishing](https://developer.chrome.com/webstore/group-publishers) and add other trusted accounts to the plugin for the Chrome and Firefox web stores, then updates can be pushed by multiple people. Any ideas and suggestions welcome. Thank you all for contributing to Deadname Remover. We recently hit **thirty thousand** Chrome installs.

column3: All events are intended for people who identify as female or transgender. Men are encouraged to attend only when noted on a specific event. A few concerns and/or questions that I have: 1. 'female or transgender' implies that one cannot be both; this language could be (I am assuming unintentionally) discouraging to trans women, who often identify as both female _and_ transgender. Perhaps this could be changed to `All events are intended for people who identify as female and/or transgender.`? 2. 'Female' implies a focus on bodies instead of identity. I am assuming that the latter is, in fact, the stronger focus of the organization. Perhaps this could be changed to `All events are intended for people who identify as women and/or transgender`? 3. Regarding `and/or transgender`: are transgender people who do not identify as women considered to fall within the category of 'Women Who Code'? If so, why? If not, it seems to me that it would make more sense if this sentence were changed to something like `All events are intended for people who identify as women`, or, to express inclusivity, which seems to be the purpose of this line in the first place, `All events are intended for people who identify as women, including trans women`. Just some thoughts; interested to know what people think!

GetSearchResults (jsonp) returns the format string for a meeting using this format as: ` "formats": "C,LGBTQI ,NC,GB", ` However the GetFormats call does not return the trailing whitespace. ``` { "key_string": "LGBTQI", "name_string": "LGBTQI", "description_string": "This meeting is focused on the needs of Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, Queer and Intersex members of NA.", "lang": "en", "id": "10", "world_id": "GL", "root_server_uri": "https://na.org.au/main_server", "format_type_enum": "FC3" } ``` This causes lookups based on a simple 'split format string by comma' to fail. Whilst this can be worked around on the client side, ideally we'd sanitise on input to prevent this from occuring (if not a historical issue).
